A handcuffed Pemberton appeared in court wearing a black
suit and striped tie.

He sat quietly, flanked by U.S. security
officers, as his lawyers asked the court to suspend proceedings in a standard trial tactic. 

The court is expected to decide Monday if a judge will grant Pemberton's request to soften his murder charge to homicide.

The murder charge, which requires premeditation, carries a maximum 40-year prison sentence, compared to 20 years for homicide. 

